    "summary": "The Spread of Theravada Buddhism (c. 300–100 BC) was the transmission of the conservative Buddhist school — emphasizing the original Pali canon, monastic discipline, and the path of individual liberation — from India into Sri Lanka and mainland Southeast Asia, where it established the religious foundation that still characterizes much of South and Southeast Asian civilization today.\n\nTheravada ('Teaching of the Elders') distinguished itself from Mahayana and other schools by strict adherence to the Pali canon established at the [[event:1213|Third Buddhist Council]] and an emphasis on the monastic path. The mission of Mahinda (son of [[event:1098|Ashoka the Great]]) to Sri Lanka around 247 BC established what would become the most important Theravada heartland outside India: Sri Lanka preserved the Pali canon when it was being lost in India and served as the source from which Theravada Buddhism spread to Burma, Thailand, Cambodia, and Laos. The transmission to these Southeast Asian countries occurred primarily between the 3rd and 13th centuries AD, making Theravada the dominant form of Buddhism in most of mainland Southeast Asia and creating distinctive cultures that combined Indian Buddhist influences with indigenous traditions — the living Theravada traditions of Thailand, Myanmar, Laos, Cambodia, and Sri Lanka trace directly to these early foundations.",
